  <h2>Overview</h2>
  <p>Tire problems are among the most common maintenance issues on electric scooters. This guide covers replacing inner tubes, patching tubes, and maintaining tires to prevent flats and maximize their lifespan.</p>

  <h2>Tools & Materials Required</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Tire levers or spoons (plastic preferred to avoid tube damage)</li>
    <li>Replacement inner tube (correct size for your scooter model)</li>
    <li>Hand pump or floor pump with suitable adapter</li>
    <li>Patch kit (for small punctures)</li>
    <li>Bicycle wrench or multi-tool</li>
    <li>Cloth for cleaning</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Before You Start</h2>
  <p>Determine your scooter's tire size by checking the sidewall of the tire (e.g., 10×2.5, 10×2.125, etc.). Ensure you have the correct replacement inner tube size. Different scooter models use different tire sizes, so verify your model's specifications.</p>

  <h2>Step-by-Step Inner Tube Replacement</h2>

  <h3>Step 1: Remove the Wheel</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Secure your scooter on a stable surface or flip it upside down</li>
    <li>Locate the axle bolt on the side opposite the motor (or brake system)</li>
    <li>Use the appropriate wrench to loosen and remove the axle bolt</li>
    <li>Slide the wheel out carefully, noting the position of any spacers or brake components</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Step 2: Deflate and Remove the Tire</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Fully deflate the tire using the valve stem</li>
    <li>Insert a tire lever between the tire and rim at a 45-degree angle</li>
    <li>Gently pry the tire edge (bead) over the rim</li>
    <li>Work around the tire with 2–3 tire levers spaced apart to avoid damaging the rim</li>
    <li>Once one side is completely free, remove the inner tube</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Step 3: Inspect the Tire</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Check the inside of the tire for thorns, glass, or sharp objects</li>
    <li>Run your fingers carefully inside (or use a cloth) to feel for embedded debris</li>
    <li>Inspect the tire for cuts, bulges, or excessive wear</li>
    <li>If the tire is damaged beyond repair, replace it as well</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Step 4: Install the New Inner Tube</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Partially inflate the new tube to give it shape (just enough to be rigid, not fully inflated)</li>
    <li>Insert the valve stem through the rim hole first</li>
    <li>Place the tube inside the tire, working around to ensure even distribution</li>
    <li>Check that the tube is not twisted or pinched</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Step 5: Reinstall the Tire Bead</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Starting opposite the valve stem, press the tire bead back onto the rim by hand</li>
    <li>Work your way around, using tire levers as needed for tight sections</li>
    <li>Be gentle to avoid pinching the new tube between the tire and rim</li>
    <li>Ensure the bead sits evenly on both sides of the rim</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Step 6: Inflate and Check</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Attach the pump to the valve stem</li>
    <li>Inflate to the recommended pressure (check your scooter's manual: typically 40–60 PSI)</li>
    <li>Visually inspect the bead seating all the way around</li>
    <li>Spin the wheel by hand to ensure it turns freely</li>
  </ol>

  <h3>Step 7: Reinstall the Wheel</h3>
  <ol>
    <li>Carefully slide the wheel back onto the axle, aligning any spacers or brake components</li>
    <li>Insert the axle bolt and tighten firmly (but not excessively)</li>
    <li>Spin the wheel to ensure it rotates smoothly without rubbing</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Patching a Punctured Tube</h2>
  <p>For small punctures, patching is faster and cheaper than replacement:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Locate the puncture by inflating the tube and listening/feeling for air leaks</li>
    <li>Mark the location with a pen</li>
    <li>Use sandpaper from a patch kit to roughen the area around the hole</li>
    <li>Apply adhesive (if included) and let it become tacky</li>
    <li>Press the patch firmly onto the hole and hold for 2–3 minutes</li>
    <li>Test the patch before reinstalling the tube</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Tire Maintenance Tips</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Check pressure regularly:</strong> Underinflated tires increase rolling resistance and heat buildup, shortening lifespan.</li>
    <li><strong>Rotate tires:</strong> If possible, swap front and rear wheels periodically to distribute wear evenly.</li>
    <li><strong>Avoid obstacles:</strong> Sharp objects, potholes, and curbs are common causes of punctures.</li>
    <li><strong>Replace worn tires:</strong> Once tread is visibly flat or the tire is cracked, replacement is necessary.</li>
    <li><strong>Store properly:</strong> If storing your scooter long-term, store tires in a cool, dry place at partial inflation.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Common Issues &amp; Troubleshooting</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Repeated punctures:</strong> Check inside the tire thoroughly for embedded objects. Consider using puncture-resistant tubes or tire sealant.</li>
    <li><strong>Bead won't seat:</strong> Ensure the tube is not pinched. Deflate slightly and try again, working around the rim methodically.</li>
    <li><strong>Wheel rubs brake or fender:</strong> Check alignment when reinstalling. Ensure spacers are in correct positions.</li>
    <li><strong>Tire bulges or wobbles:</strong> Likely a bent rim or structural damage. The wheel may need professional repair or replacement.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>When to Call a Professional</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Bent or dented rims</li>
    <li>Damaged tire sidewalls or large cuts</li>
    <li>Bearing or spoke issues</li>
    <li>Motor or brake complications</li>
  </ul>

